<div id="review_61238418" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/61238418" />
    <a title="R." class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/184928-r"><img alt="R." src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1509742903p2/184928.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/61238418?book_show_action=true">Jun 26, 2009</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="R." class="user" itemprop="url" name="R." href="/user/show/184928-r">R.</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780679736660" href="/book/show/216368.The_Three_Stigmata_of_Palmer_Eldritch">review of another edition</a>

          <div><span class="uitext greyText">Recommends it for: </span>
           <span class="uitext reviewText">Cyberpunks and Christians</span></div>

        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/184928-r?shelf=2009">2009</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer61238418" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer18415815633429360272">An incredibly prescient satire on multimedia* addiction - losing oneself in artificial environments to escape (or at least muffle) an undesirable reality. <br/><br/>The picture PKD paints of the sad Martian colonists taking drugs and playing with dolls (<i>becoming one with the dolls</i>) reminds me of the...stereotypical...image the world has of the American nerd stuffing himself with junkfood and playing Sims, losing track of the time, of the day while living a better - or at least dynamic - life on a more vib</span>
  <span id="freeText18415815633429360272" style="display:none">An incredibly prescient satire on multimedia* addiction - losing oneself in artificial environments to escape (or at least muffle) an undesirable reality. <br /><br />The picture PKD paints of the sad Martian colonists taking drugs and playing with dolls (<i>becoming one with the dolls</i>) reminds me of the...stereotypical...image the world has of the American nerd stuffing himself with junkfood and playing Sims, losing track of the time, of the day while living a better - or at least dynamic - life on a more vibrant earth.<br /><br />...ultimately a mind-blowing foray into Gnostic theology; also, the bit about the telepathic Martian jackal was hilarious.<br /><br />*Keep in mind that in PKD's time, multimedia was...the telephone, the television and the radio. Though, sure...there were pirate radio broadcasts and TV broadcasts, and the telephone lines were open to hackers seeking free long distance calls - no doubt PKD's milieu incorporated a phreaker or two among the freaks - but, still, credit where credit is due. And credit <i>is</i> due.</span>
  <a data-text-id="18415815633429360272" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


